<TEXT>
a group of journalists and engineers are fighting 
a huge dam project on the yangtze river marking the first time 
chinese intellectuals have united for an environmental cause 
the group which is to hold its first news conference tuesday 
has published a book criticizing the three gorges hydroelectric 
project a 15000megawatt facility that would be the largest water 
power project in the world 
the book represents the first time chinese journalists have 
worked together based on their conscience not on what the 
staterun press has told them to do said dai qing editor of the 
book prepared by journalists from the peoples daily xinhua news 
agency and other leading publications 
ms dai an editor at the prestigious guangming daily said she 
organized opposition because huge industrial projects need to be 
discussed by all of society not just by a few men in a ministry 
somewhere 
she said all the journalists and engineers participating in the 
group are worried about chinas environment which has deteriorated 
rapidly during the past 10 years of swift economic growth 
her comments also come as an increasing number of chinese 
intellectuals are challenging the governments monopoly on 
decisionmaking power 
since the 1949 revolution my country has undertaken thousands 
of mistaken projects she said but you would think that in a 
planned economy things would be carried out scientifically thats 
not the case in china 
in the 1950s and 1960s she said industrial projects were pushed 
on their political merits indeed opponents of the three gorges 
project were branded as rightists in political campaigns in 
those days 
now government ministries compete for scarce resources for their 
projects paying little heed to the interests of the nation as a 
whole she said 
it may be less political but the behavior is just as harmful 
to the country she said 
ms dai said she realized she was risking her job and possibly 
her future by openly voicing her opinion 
but that doesnt bother me she said i cannot keep 
silent 
since the communist revolution chinese politicians have been 
considering a plan to build a 610foot dam on the yangtze river near 
the border of sichuan and hubei provinces in central china 
the dam would block the famous three gorges covering forever the 
vistas celebrated on chinese scroll paintings for centuries 
the project would tame the perennial floods of the mighty 
yangtze the third longest river in the world after the nile and the 
amazon it also would provide energy to nearby cities like chunking 
chinas biggest urban center with 16 million people 
factories in chunking are idle at least 20 percent of the time 
because they lack power 
in january it looked like the project would be delayed five 
years when vicepremier yao yilin said economic difficulties would 
hold up the plan but last week backers of the project held a news 
conference and said yao was only expressing his personal opinion 
the project would have to tackle massive problems 
about 1 million people will have to be moved to make room for a 
huge reservoir containing 519 trillion gallons of water according 
to a chinese scientist who has worked on the project for several 
decades 
the dam is planned for an area prone to earthquakes 
one jolt and wuhan a major industrial center east of the 
planned dam will be wiped out said the scientist who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
finally much of the land around the dam has been deforested by 
peasants seeking wood for their homes and for energy 
we fear the dam will turn the center of china into a big mud 
puddle he said the damage to the environment could be 
catastrophic 
in the face of the problems china has asked for foreign advice 
in 1980 an american team of engineers said the project was so 
dangerous it would be like putting an atomic bomb on chinas 
head according to chinese documents obtained here 
the engineers report says china should concentrate on tapping 
the sparsely populated upper reaches of the yangtze river for power 
it also raises concerns about the destruction of the three 
gorges the chinese equivalent of north americas grand canyon 
</TEXT>
