a smalltown lawyer ordered by federal 
courts to represent convicts says the us supreme court should let 
him off the case because he would not be able to provide competent 
courtroom representation 
i consider myself a business lawyer said john a mallard 
34 whose case was scheduled to go before the high court tuesday 
i consider myself very competent to read the law construe the 
law and argue the law but not to take on some of these courtroom 
responsibilities he said 
mallard a partner in a law firm in this southeastern iowa town 
of 9500 people was picked to represent three inmates in june 1987 
from a list of more than 100 attorneys compiled by the volunteer 
lawyers project a joint venture of the legal services corp of iowa 
and the iowa state bar association 
the inmates at the iowa state penitentiary at fort madison filed 
a civil rights lawsuit alleging that guards and officials mistreated 
them endangered their lives by revealing they were informants and 
filed false disciplinary reports against them one inmate is out on 
parole 
courts routinely assign lawyers to represent indigent defendants 
in criminal cases and the lawyers are paid at taxpayer expense 
which is generally a fraction of what they normally could receive 
in civil rights lawsuits lawyers are paid expenses and may be paid 
a part of any damages won by their clients 
mallards request to be taken off the case was denied by a us 
magistrate a federal district judge and the 8th us circuit court 
of appeals 
he contends those decisions misinterpreted an 1892 federal 
statute that says the court may request rather than order an 
attorney to represent an indigent defendant 
the iowa attorney generals office which will argue the case 
against mallard says he is shirking his obligations 
when a judge asks you to help him or her out in the 
administration of justice its your duty and obligation to say 
yes and to do your best job deputy attorney general gordon 
allen said earlier this month but in mr mallards case he 
simply didnt say that he said i dont want to play i dont want 
to come to your party 
mr mallard is not incompetent allen said hes carrying 
this all the way to the supreme court and doing an admirable job 
incompetency by itself is not a reason for exclusion of your 
responsibility 
unfortunately for the inmates their case has just done 
nothing its gone nowhere while we have litigated mr mallards 
responsibility to represent them 
the case is being closely watched by lawyers said jack londen 
chairman of the california bar associations legal services section 
were very troubled by saddling a client with a lawyer whos 
unwilling to represent the client said londen who filed a 
