<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let 
brunswick ga collect a 324000 reimbursement it won and then 
lost from the federal government for legal costs incurred in a 
fight over flood control 
the justices without comment let stand a federal appeals court 
ruling that the coastal city does not qualify for the reimbursement 
the dispute dates back to brunswicks request in the early 1980s 
to participate in the federally subsidized national flood insurance 
program for communities that carefully control development of land 
likely to be flooded 
in 1985 brunswick sued the federal emergency management agency 
which runs the program and others over alleged errors in 
calculating brunswicks eligibility 
the lawsuit ended in a settlement prior to any trial and a 
federal trial judge ordered the government to pay brunswick 324000 
for lawyer fees and other costs the city had incurred 
the award was made under the equal access to justice act under 
that law a local government that engages the federal government in 
legal battle is eligible for reimbursement if its net worth is less 
than 7 million and the federal governments position in the dispute 
was not substantially justified 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals last july 11 threw out the 
324000 award on two grounds it said brunswicks net worth exceeds 
7 million and the federal governments position in the flood 
control dispute was substantially justified 
on the networth issue justice department lawyers relied on the 
citys annual financial report showing total municipal equity to 
be just over 22 million when the lawsuit was filed they said that 
figure reflected the citys net worth 
but city lawyers said the net worth term used in the equal 
access to justice act should not include those assets generally not 
available to pay off debts 
the citys water and sewer system wrongly was counted as an asset 
because its worth is not available for debt payment the citys 
lawyers argued 
the 11th circuit court said net worth is determined by 
subtracting total liabilities from total assets including 
the citys water and sewer system 
the appeals court also ruled that us district judge anthony 
alaimo abused his discretion in deciding that the federal 
governments legal position in the underlying dispute had not been 
substantially justified 
the case is brunswick vs us 88948 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

