<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling that 
someone who plans a bank robbery but is arrested before actually 
moving toward the bank may not be convicted of violating a federal 
law prohibiting attempted bank robbery 
the court over two dissenting votes rejected a justice 
department appeal that sought reinstatement of an attempted bank 
robbery conviction in a california case 
justices byron r white and harry a blackmun voted to hear 
arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such review 
the case stems from the arrest of reginald dean still on aug 7 
1985 in roseville calif 
responding to a tip from a passerby police found still sitting 
in a van parked some 200 feet from the security pacific bank 
the vans motor was running when police arrived and still put it 
in reverse and drove off police caught up with him and arrested him 
police said he told them you did a good job you caught me 
five minutes before i was going to rob a bank 
he said he confessed because of incriminating evidence inside the 
van including a blond wig a phony bomb and a note demanding money 
that still said he intended to present to a teller at a driveup 
window 
police said still told them his confession was merely frosting 
on the cake because of the other evidence 
he was convicted in federal court of attempted bank robbery and 
interstate transporation of a stolen vehicle the van he said he 
intended to use in the robbery still was sentenced to 15 years in 
prison 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals upheld the stolen van 
conviction but threw out the conviction for attempted bank robbery 
stills intent to rob the security pacific national bank was 
clearly established the appeals court said 
but the facts do not establish either actual movement toward 
the bank or actions that are analytically similar to such 
movement the appeals court said without that there can be no 
conviction for attempted bank robbery it added 
justice department lawyers said the appeals court ruling 
establishes a dangerous precedent 
attempts are punished as a crime because of the great need to 
stop offenses from occurring department lawyers said 
a robbery may be only moments away even though the robber has 
not yet begun to assault the bank they continued society 
should be free to intervene in order not only to stop a crime from 
coming to pass but also to punish the defendant for putting 
innocent parties at risk of the loss of their property serious 
injury or death 
the governments appeal said the 9th circuit court ruling which 
is binding law in arizona alaska california hawaii idaho 
montana nevada oregon and washington state is in conflict with 
other federal courts 
fbi statistics show that in 1987 nearly half of all robberies of 
federally insured financial institutions occurred in states within 
the 9th circuit the government said 
the case is us vs still 88581 
</TEXT>
