<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether the rights of white criminal defendants may be violated when 
blacks are excluded from serving as jurors in their trials 
the justices said they will hear an appeal by daniel holland a 
chicagoarea white man sentenced to 85 years in prison for rape 
kidnaping and armed robbery 
the high court in 1986 ruled that prosecutors never may 
disqualify potential jurors based on their race the ruling 
dramatically curtailed the traditonally broad power of prosecutors 
to eliminate prospective jurors from trials by using peremptory or 
automatic challenges 
but that case involved a black defendant and jurors of his race 
the justices have not decided whether exclusion of black jurors in 
this manner can violate the rights of a white defendant 
in hollands case two blacks among the more than 30 prospective 
jurors were excluded by the prosecution from serving on the panel 
that eventually convicted him 
prosecutors said they were not motivated by racial considerations 
when they used their peremptory challenges to exclude the two 
blacks a man and a woman from the jury 
the illinois supreme court said that as a white person holland 
lacked legal standing to raise the issue of whether race played a 
part in the exclusion of the two blacks 
we decline to address this issue because we find that the 
defendant a caucasian does not have standing to assert such a 
constitutional violation the state court said 
the state court also rejected hollands argument that he was 
denied his constitutional right to be tried by a fair crosssection 
of the community 
holland was convicted in the rape and kidnaping of a des plaines 
ill teenage girl on may 4 1980 
prosecutors said holland gave a ride to the girl and her 
boyfriend they said he forced the boyfriend to leave the car and 
raped the girl at knifepoint 
holland was arrested hours after the assault when a police 
stopped his car because it had no rear license plate 
the case is holland vs illinois 885050 
</TEXT>
