<TEXT>
the governors of michigan iowa ohio 
missouri minnesota wisconsin and indiana agreed monday to share 
the cost of a lowlevel nuclear waste site said gov james 
blanchard of michigan 
in january blanchard had halted site selection in michigan until 
the other states in the midwest interstate lowlevel radioactive 
waste compact met demands designed to ensure michigan bore only its 
fair share of the financial burden 
he ordered the siteselection process to resume after the states 
agreed to his terms 
no one wants to be left holding the bag with the lowlevel 
waste issue blanchard said in announcing the agreement 
blanchard and the governors of iowa ohio missouri minnesota 
wisconsin and indiana reached agreement on the waste site monday 
after two days of conferences during the national governors 
association winter meeting 
we support the party states sharing reponsibility and liability 
for those expenses not paid for by insurance or the funds 
established in michigan statute and that share be based on a 
prorated amount according to the amount of waste generated in each 
state the governors said in a joint letter to blanchard 
the governors also agreed that each state would continue to pay 
its share of the disposal sites operation even if the state 
withdraws from the midwest compact 
the disposal plant would cost an estimated 300 million over its 
20year life said jd snyder blanchards aide dealing with 
environmental issues 
with the agrement michigans share could be less than onethird 
of that amount snyder said 
had the other states failed to agree to blanchards terms 
michigan would have had to pay the full cost of building and 
operating the plant 
the state legislatures would need to approve spending on the 
site blanchard said adding he foresaw no difficulty in obtaining 
the funding 
michigan was selected as the site for the nuclear waste dump 
because it generates the most radioactive waste in the region 
michigan generated about 27000 cubic feet of lowlevel 
radioactive waste last year from nuclear plants research 
institutions and hospitals 
michigans nuclear waste now goes to sites in south carolina and 
washington whose governors threatened to refuse to accept michigan 
waste unless blanchard rescinded his order halting site selection 
