<TEXT>
the gumbo clay of central louisiana is 
wearing out the brakes on the new 25000 allterrain vehicles the 
army is buying to replace the venerable jeep 
army posts around the world are using the new high mobility 
multipurpose wheeled vehicle but the brake problem appears unique 
to those used at fort polk said post spokesman orina fulton 
about 10 percent of the posts 700 hmmwvs are showing premature 
wear on the brake pads fulton said the vehicles were delivered in 
july and brake trouble showed up in december he said 
he blamed the thick gumbo clay so called because of its soft 
sticky consistency that is common in louisiana 
if youre familiar with fort polk and the surrounding areas it 
looks like sand on top but underneath youve got soft red clay 
fulton said the soil gets onto the brake pads and is staying 
there 
jeeps had no trouble with the clay because they had enclosed drum 
brakes the new vehicle described as a larger wider version of the 
jeep has exposed disc brakes fulton said 
the vehicle nicknamed the hummer is manufactured in mishawaka 
ind by am general corp a division of the ltv missiles amp 
electronics group 
am general is testing a new system that would alleviate the 
problem he said 
