<TEXT>
an army warrant officer accused of spying for 
the warsaw pact has waived his right to a grand jurytype proceeding 
and will face an immediate courtmartial starting next week the 
service said monday 
the case has been referred to trial as a noncapital case 
however meaning if convicted the maximum punishment would be life 
in prison the army added 
warrant officer james w hall 30 of new york city was arrested 
dec 21 near savannah ga after allegedly admitting to an fbi 
undercover agent that he had been passing classified intelligence 
information to the soviets and east germans for the past six years 
on jan 4 hall was formally charged with 10 counts of espionage 
attempted espionage and failing to obey regulations 
the army has asserted that hall an intelligence analyst with a 
top secret security clearance delivered exposed film and documents 
dealing with communications intelligence a means of defense or 
retaliation against largescale attack war plans and military 
satellites 
at the time of his arrest hall was assigned to the 24th infantry 
division and worked as an intelligence analyst in the armys g2 
intelligence section he joined the army in september 1976 and spent 
most of his career working in europe as an analyst of intercepted 
radio and telephone traffic and coded messages 
legally hall could have insisted the army conduct a socalled 
article 32 hearing a proceeding that resembles a civilian grand 
jury hearing to determine if a courtmartial is warranted 
the soldier decided to waive that hearing however and the 
courtmartial of warrant officer hall will convene on march 6 1989 
at fort mcnair washington dc the army added 
it is anticipated that hall as is his right will request to 
be tried by judge alone he will be tried by military judge col 
howard c eggers the chief of the united states army trial 
judiciary 
it was not immediately clear why the case against hall was being 
referred to trial as a noncapital case 
under a revision to the uniform code of military justice approved 
by congress several years ago the most serious espionage cases can 
be tried as capital cases with the death penalty as maximum 
punishment 
the army said monday that much of the proceeding involving hall 
would be closed to the media and public because of the classified 
nature of the evidence 
</TEXT>
