<TEXT>
an insurance executive doing volunteer 
work in an aids hospice in toronto last year asked a dying man what 
he could do to help and the patient said he could help him die 
with a little more dignity 
the volunteer ron barbaro president of the canadian branch of 
prudential insurance co of america soon found a way for his 
company to pay death benefits to the dying a program being hailed 
by aids support groups 
here was a situation where this young mans parents were in 
europe and he was alone barbaro recalled during a recent 
telephone interview with the san jose mercury news when he died 
there would be a fair amount of money 20000 or 25000 and yet 
he had nothing right now 
barbaro could do little to help the young man before he died but 
barbaro 56 vowed that i would find a way to give some living 
benefits from our industry to other terminally ill patients 
working with company lawyers actuaries and underwriters he came 
up with the first policy to give terminally ill patients whether 
dying of aids or other causes part of their benefits before they 
die 
we have been looking for a long time to see some leadership 
from the insurance industry in the aids crisis and i think this 
is very creative and a tremendous step forward said leonard 
graff legal director of national gay rights advocates in san 
francisco he said he thought its a very generous and caring 
thing for them to do 
in the past year hundreds of thousands of dollars have been paid 
out with benefits ranging from 40 percent to 70 percent of the 
total benefit depending on the circumstances the remainder of the 
benefits are paid to the beneficiary when the patient dies 
gerald haims an insurance analyst with seidler amdec securities 
in los angeles said the move was not only a humanitarian gesture 
but it makes good dollars and cents too 
this is something prudential can really capitalize on said 
haims can you imagine the appeal in terms of advertising not 
only would you have an immediate following among gay and lesbian 
communities but every humanitarian out there will be impressed by 
it im impressed by it 
barbaro said he has received many inquiries from other insurance 
officials in canada and the united states 
theyre looking very seriously at it because theres no 
downside said barbaro noting that insurance companies dont lose 
money by making payments in advance 
conventional wisdom has always been that you dont pay a claim 
until somebody has died he said but my question was why not 
if the numbers work out 
joseph v vecchione prudentials vice president for public 
relations in the united states said the payments are not being made 
to policyholders in the us because there are many legal 
difficulties in this country which would have to be resolved 
canadian laws are different and our attorneys there feel we can 
proceed he said we will take a close look at what ensues in 
canada 
ben schatz director of the groups aids civil rights project and 
a member of the aids advisory committee of the national association 
of insurance commissioners called prudentials policy unique in 
the insurance industry and said it shows profits and compassion 
do not necessarily have to conflict 
we have seen depressingly few creative health approaches coming 
out of the insurance industry said schatz its nice to see an 
exception 
