<TEXT>
the governor and a former ku klux klan 
grand wizard recently elected to the state legislature locked horns 
monday over setting aside some state highway contracts for 
blackowned companies 
we have a very clear process of racial discrimination going on 
in this bill rep david duke said during an appearance before the 
house appropriations committee 
gov buddy roemer also making an appearance before the 
committee said he did not believe the minority setasides would be 
a permanent fixture in awarding highway contracts they are only a 
transition the democrat said 
duke a republican from suburban new orleans was elected to the 
state legislature feb 18 after a heated campaign in which he drew 
opposition from president bush former president reagan and most of 
the areas political elite 
he is not a member of the appropriations panel like the 
governor he appeared to testify about the setaside programs 
for duke it was one of the first opportunities to address a 
campaign pledge to oppose special treatment for blacks 
the committee voted 123 against duke and for the governor 
sending the bill to the house floor for debate 
under setasides a portion of government contracts are reserved 
for minorityowned companies as a remedy for past discrimination 
roemer who wants a 15 billion program for highways airports 
and ports financed by an additional 4cent tax on gasoline said the 
bill would make sure the entire state moves together in economic 
development 
the governor said his administration wanted to limit such 
programs to 10 percent of the total 
but duke elected after campaigning against setaside programs 
said the bill would discriminate against white contractors 
he claimed roemers transportation program could cost up to 200 
million more if setaside programs were used he said 
duke a 38yearold republican from suburban new orleans quit 
the klan in 1980 in a leadership dispute and set up his own 
organization the national association for the advancement of white 
people 
rep sherman copelin a black democrat from new orleans said the 
bill had been drawn with the help of the associated general 
contractors the states largest contracting group 
according to the bill the governor would be required to have a 
study committee determine whether black contractors have been 
discriminated against the legislature would be in charge of drawing 
up guidelines for the setaside program if the study found 
discrimination 
if lawmakers did not act by june 30 roemer could impose 
guidelines by executive order 
the us supreme court earlier this year struck down a richmond 
va plan to set aside 30 percent of the value of public works 
projects for companies at least halfowned by minorities because the 
city could not prove minority contractors were being discriminated 
against 
