<TEXT>
archaeologists have begun unearthing the 
remains of a 17thcentury spanish mission that they located in a 
pasture with the help of an airborne heat sensor developed by nasa 
its fantastic says jerry milanich curator in archaeology 
at the university of floridas florida museum of natural history 
i never saw anything so magical in my life he said of the 
computergenerated map that revealed the outlines of what little is 
left of the mission santa fe de toloco 
in the past few weeks teams headed by milanich have unearthed 
what they are convinced are the outlines of the missions three main 
buildings the kitchen the priests residence and the church they 
also have found the missions cemetery 
these relics have been hidden since 1702 when british soldiers 
and their indian allies burned and looted the centuryold santa fe 
de toloco soon ruins were plowed into the soil or covered by 
natural soil buildup 
on christmas eve 1986 a field crew headed by graduate student 
ken johnson stumbled across pottery spikes and clay near the santa 
fe river in alachua county north of the schools campus in 
gainesville using spanish documents they were able to narrow the 
location of santa fe de toloco to within 10 miles 
milanich and researchers contracted with the space remote sensing 
center a national aeronautics and space administrationsupported 
research center in mississippi last april a plane outfitted with a 
heatsensing scanner flew over the site 
computers analyzed the sites radiated heat to differentiate 
surrounding soil from clay and other early construction materials 
which absorb heat differently they then created a color image which 
can show differences in heat of as little as a half degree 
the instruments will revolutionize archaeology milanich said 
noting they saved at least 10000 in this instance and as much as 
five years of work 
once the imagery pinpointed parts of the missions remnants digs 
could focus on specific areas and avoid damaging important sections 
of the site he said 
during the latter half of the 16th century and all of the 17th 
century more than 40 mission outposts dotted la florida the name 
given the entire known north american continent during the two 
centuries spain dominated the area 
one chain of missions stretched from st augustine north to 
coastal south carolina while another extended west across the 
florida panhandle one remnant of the trails that connected them is 
a dirt alley between homes on the west side of gainesville 
the indigenous indians were eventually wiped out by european 
soldiers and diseases seminoles from the north took their place 
the missionaries abandoned their attempt to bring christianity to 
the natives 
</TEXT>
