a car bomb explosion killed a 
former senior police officer as he drove in east belfast on monday 
and the irish republican army claimed responsibility its second 
victim in two days 
police said the victim was a catholic who retired from the force 
three years ago 
in cookstown in the center of the province the army defused a 
200pound car bomb found in the center of a predominantly protestant 
housing estate discovery of the bomb forced about 70 families to 
sleep elsewhere monday night 
in londonderry police said a 6pound bomb packed with nails was 
found near an elementary school a police spokesman called the bomb 
fiendish and completely indiscriminate 
police also were questioning two men in londonderry following 
discovery of a cache of bombmaking ingredients 
the outlawed ira said the former officer killed on monday had not 
severed his ties with the royal ulster constabulary the provinces 
police force 
a police spokesman speaking on condition of anonymity called 
the ira statement a repugnant tissue of lies 
the mainly catholic ira has targeted soldiers and police in its 
fight to drive the british from northern ireland and unite the 
protestantdominated province with the overwhelmingly catholic 
republic of ireland 
police on monday identified a man shot dead sunday night by the 
ira as joseph fenton 35 
the ira accused fenton also a catholic of being a british 
agent police said they were not aware of any connections between 
fenton and the security forces 
