<TEXT>
the house ethics committee monday began an 
exhaustive review of a special counsels investigative report on 
alleged ethics violations of speaker jim wright and members said 
they would be in no rush to finish 
the panels closeddoor deliberations are being held in strict 
secrecy and committee chairman rep julian dixon dcalif said he 
expects no announcement of any results until the week of march 13 
i think everyones getting their questions answered said 
rep john t myers of indiana the panels senior republican after 
seven hours of deliberations we are dealing with very sensitive 
matters here peoples careers 
the committee is scheduled to meet again tuesday wednesday and 
thursday and panel members have been asked to keep their calendars 
clear next week as well 
dixon said the special outside counsel hired to investigate the 
wright matter richard j phelan is presenting his findings count 
by count members can then ask questions and wrights lawyer 
william c oldaker can comment on the evidence he said 
wright dtexas is alleged in a sixcount resolution to have 
abused his office for personal financial gain the charges include 
using a congressional aide to help compile a book on which wright 
earned some 55000 in royalties and using a condominium in his 
hometown of fort worth without paying full market value 
he also is alleged to have improperly lobbied federal officials 
on behalf of texas savings and loan institutions and lobbied for a 
gas venture in which he had a financial stake 
wright has steadfastly denied violating any law or rule of the 
house although he has conceded he might have done some things 
differently if he had them to do over 
the committee has spent nearly 1 million on the probe which 
began in june most of it for phelans legal fees his report to the 
committee runs about 450 pages and includes only findings of fact on 
the six allegations against wright but no recommendations on 
whether the facts warrant disciplinary action said one committee 
source speaking only on condition of anonymity 
the source said phelan has used the broadest possible 
interpretation of each of the six counts and has in some cases 
divided them into subcategories that enabled phelan for example 
to go into wrights financial dealings with fort worth business 
partner george mallick under the heading of looking into the 
condominium which was owned by mallicks son 
myers said the presence of oldaker was unusual but he added 
were just trying to be as generous as we can committee rules 
provide that a member who is the subject of an investigation can be 
given a chance to comment on the allegations 
the process is adversarial in the sense that both sides will 
represent their points of view dixon said the facts are always 
subject to interpretation 
oldaker had no comment on the probe as he entered the hearing 
room except to say the process has gone on for a long period of 
time we hope for an early resolution 
the committees current deliberations are the culmination of a 
process known as a preliminary inquiry the panels equivalent of a 
grand jury investigation 
dixon said the committee will hear the presentations of the two 
lawyers and discuss the findings then decide whether to take the 
next step in the process issuing a statement of alleged violation 
which is akin to an indictment 
wright has not been given a copy of phelans report and was not 
scheduled to attend the deliberations dixon said 
</TEXT>
