<TEXT>
a comprehensive agreement to clean up the 
nations most contaminated nuclear weaponsproduction site was 
signed monday by the federal government and washington state but 
the pact had no guarantee that money will be available to complete 
the job at the hanford nuclear reservation 
at a signing ceremony state and federal officials said the 
landmark agreement will provide a clear road map for 
cleaning up the 570 square mile reservation in washington state and 
serve as a model for other energy department weapons plants 
the department also made public monday documents that estimated 
five billion cubic yards of hazardous solid and liquid wastes both 
radioactive and toxic have been disposed of at hanford 
the documents said that abovebackground concentrations of 
such substances as tritium iodine129 uranium and cyanide have 
been found in the groundwater beneath the reservation and may 
threaten the nearby columbia river 
these materials have toxic carcinogenic mutagenic or 
teratogenic effects on humans and other life forms the documents 
said adding that there continue to be releases of hazardous 
compounds 
under the agreement announced monday the department has promised 
to seek 28 billion for the hanford clean up over five years but 
the appropriation has yet to receive the blessing of the white house 
budget office and will eventually have to be approved by congress 
after five years the agreement calls for the state and the 
energy department to sit down and come up with additional requests 
to finance continued cleanup which by department estimates could 
cost 57 billion 
we are extremely satisfied with the money provisions said 
washington gov booth gardner 
key provisions of the hanford action cleanup action plan 
include 
an accelerated program for actually cleaning up the reservation 
over 30 years rather than 50 years as originally envisioned 
specific cleanup milestones doe could be fined up to 10000 
per week for failing to meet the milestones 
clear delineation of duties between the state the energy 
department and the federal environmental protection agency 
an agreement which the justice department has agreed to 
allowing the state or members of the general public to enforce the 
agreement by filing a lawsuit if necessary 
in addition the federal government has agreed to provide 
washington state 29 million over three years to fund the states 
oversight role 
the agreement was reached after more than a year of negotiations 
and amid threats that the state would go to court if negotiations 
failed 
besides being the most contaminated of the energy departments 16 
nuclear weaponsproductions sites the hanford reservation is 
expected to be the most costly to clean up and take the longest 
j winston porter an assistant epa administration said the 
hanford site offers the toughest problems of any site 
it will be the largest clean up in terms of time cost and 
complexity said porter 
stored at hanford is more than 60 percent of the nations 
highlevel radioactive waste generated by weapons programs dating 
back to world war ii 
scientists at the reservation worked on the bomb that was dropped 
at nagasaki in the 1950s hanford was one of the largest weapons 
production complexes 
at present only one commercial nuclear power plant is operating 
at the reservation and the department has announced plans to phase 
out all weapons production activities at the site 
</TEXT>
