<TEXT>
victor paz estenssoro is in the final 
months of a presidency that brought a stability rarely seen before 
in bolivia south americas poorest nation 
in a country that has had 75 governments in 163 years of 
independence just completing a presidential term is accomplishment 
and few other than paz estenssoro have been able to do it 
of the 75 governments only 38 were constitutionally elected the 
rest came about by military coup or some other unconstitutional 
manipulation or revolution 
paz estenssoro himself led two revolutions a leftist one in the 
1950s and a conservative one three decades later 
when he took office after the conservative one bolivia was in 
the grips of a dizzying 24000percent inflation it took 165000 
bolivian pesos to buy one dollars worth of goods and interest rates 
were soaring around 800 percent 
paz estenssoro brought the economy back to its feet but to do so 
he had to undo what he had done in his first revolution 
his third presidential term ends aug 6 the 164th anniversary of 
independence from spain at 81 he plans to retire and turn the 
future of bolivias 67 million people over to the candidate who is 
elected in presidential balloting may 17 
paz estenssoro wishes to be remembered as the man who was able 
to carry out two revolutions said his minister of information 
herman antelo 
paz estenssoro first assumed the presidency in 1952 returning 
from exile at the end of a unionbacked popular revolution that 
toppled a military government and shattered the oligarchic control 
of a small group of tin mining barons 
his government was considered one of the most radical of its time 
in south america it nationalized the tin mines gave peasants the 
right to vote and provided them with land by breaking up large 
estates 
he lost in the 1956 elections but returned to office by winning 
the vote four years later he completed that term and was 
reelected but toppled in a military coup in late 1964 
twenty one years later in 1985 he again became president this 
time on a conservative platform he said times had changed and a 
new approach was needed to solve bolivias problems 
he dismantled the state mining monopoly he had created 
modernized the economy and successfully challenged the authority of 
leftist labor unions that flourished during the 1952 revolution 
the courage and commitment demonstrated by bolivia under the 
presidency of victor paz estenssoro are exemplary and certainly 
underappreciated abroad us ambassador robert gelbard said in 
an interview 
no other democratic government in latin america has 
demonstrated the resolve to undertake a program of fundamental 
structural change and then to stick by it 
when he began this latest term the staggering economy had led to 
widespread social unrest and virtually all foreign economic 
assistance had been cut off 
his government prescribed harsh remedies the currency was 
devalued by 94 percent all price supports were lifted wages frozen 
and 17 of the 21 governmentrun mines were shut down as highly 
unprofitable of the nations 26500 miners 21000 lost their jobs 
while the bolivian workers central maintains that most of the 
fired miners remain unemployed information minister antelo said 
some 18000 have found other work 
in all 35000 government employees were dismissed 
the workers central responded to the austerity measures with a 
general strike but paz estenssoro broke it by declaring a state of 
seige and sending labor leaders to internment camps 
by 1988 inflation had plunged to 21 percent labor unrest has 
eased in part because of an emergency public works program launched 
with 100 million in aid from the world bank and european 
governments the country now enjoys a renewed steady flow of 
foreign aid 
to stop corruption outside agencies were hired to handle 
government purchases and contracts french and english companies 
have been put in charge of imports certifying their quality and 
collecting duties 
the tax system was overhauled and computerized and tax revenues 
have tripled in three years 
ambassador gelbard said paz estenssoros program could serve as 
a model for other countries struggling with the burdens of a statist 
tradition despite the formidable problems that the country still 
confronts the chances of bolivia generating consistent economic 
growth and consolidating its hold on democracy are very good 
the reforms have carried a steep social cost however 
malnutrition and illiteracy still plague most of bolivias 
largely indian population 
the minimum monthly wage is the equivalent of 40 while the 
prices of most food products are comparable to those in the united 
states 
unemployment hovers above 20 percent but is declining 
the governments economic policies have led to starvation wages 
for the working class charged simon reyes secretary general of 
the workers central 
he claimed the government had capitulated to the demands of the 
international banking community while factories are closing and 
workers earning power is shrinking 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

