<TEXT>
the sandbags are gone in basra iraqs second 
largest city after years of battering by the iranians in the 
persian gulf war a new city is rising from the rubble 
its going to be the best city in iraq said a bank manager 
who identified himself only as simon everythings going to be 
new 
the scars of ferocious iranian missile attacks and artillery 
bombardments are still everywhere shrapnelscarred buildings 
groves of decapitated palm trees abandoned tanks sunken ships in 
the shattalarab waterway that meanders through the city to the 
persian gulf 
but the souk or market is booming the sheraton hotel on the 
bank of the muddy shattalarab peppered by direct shell hits and 
deserted for the last two years opened for business again in 
february 
it was a dispute over territorial claims to the stattalarab 
that led to the war in 1980 
the two daily flights from baghdad iraqs capital to basras 
newly reopened airport are packed with businessmen including 
construction engineers who have come to lobby officials for 
contracts 
on a recent visit president saddam hussein criticized the slow 
pace of rebuilding in a city that symbolized iraqs defense against 
six years of iranian offensives 
the people of basra deserve their city to be beautiful and more 
organized he said 
his government has pledged 5 billion to repair the damage and 
make basra the centerpiece of a new international industrial zone 
founded 1400 years ago and known as the venice of the east 
because of its network of canals basra was iraqs main port with a 
prewar population of 15 million it is just 15 miles from iran 
ayatollah ruhollah khomeinis iranian forces battled to within 
six miles of basras eastern outskirts in early 1987 putting it 
within easy artillery range 
in the bombardments 90 percent of basras buildings were 
