flashpoint grp records tom scott 
 
saxophonist tom scott has played it seems with everybody 
a short list of those hes backed includes barbra streisand 
steely dan paul mccartney and joni mitchell he has written scores 
for movies and even the themes for two 1970s tv shows starsky and 
hutch and the streets of san francisco 
in between such projects scott sometimes with his everchanging 
band the la express has found time to make solo records of 
lightweight jazzrock fusion meticulously produced and somewhat 
devoid of any spark 
the same holds true for flashpoint 
the opening cut get a grip sets the tone for the album 
with its uptempo melody overdubbed saxophone solos and shifty 
rhythm scotts penchant for overdubbing tenor and alto saxes 
creates a fuller sound but prevents him from straying too far from 
the melody robbing his solos of spontaneity 
lost in love and night drifter are both moodier slower 
pieces that showcase scotts tenor sax runs while the title cut is 
the most adventurous with its synthesizersaxophone harmony and 
machinelike rhythm 
scott is a talented composer producer and sideman but as a solo 
act he shows little imagination his music while pleasant enough 
begs for something to set it apart from the crowd 
by curt anderson associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
tshirt epic the crickets 
 
the first album in years by the crickets is an unexpected little 
pleasure especially if it is approached without lofty expectations 
former buddy holly sidekicks ji allison and joe mauldin are 
joined on tshirt by singerguitarist gordon payne for 10 songs 
that happily dont lapse into sentimental reminiscences or futile 
attempts to recreate the late rockers magic 
they do a good job playing breezy goodtime rock n roll the 
sort of thing holly might be doing today had he lived and stopped 
progressing musically past 1959 
its unpretentious fun and instantly likeable 
one song rises above the rest the paul mccartneyproduced title 
cut its the most overtly hollyesque song here with an 
irresistible handclapping guitarstrumming chorus dont tell me 
that love hurtsi read the book i saw the movie got the tshirt 
the crickets also poke fun at themselves in the bouncy three 
piece noting how many musicians have been in and out of the band 
since holly split from the group shortly before his death 
there have been they sing more crickets than a dogs got 
fleas but weve cut it down to a threepiece then noting the 
advantages of a smaller group the overheads down and the moneys 
increased 
such high points are not sustained over the entire album though 
and the sappy ballad the weekend and the unnecessary car song 
cruise in it threaten to drag things down 
but the crickets make up in spirit for the few weak spots making 
tshirt a wellfitting comfortable record 
by marc rice associated press writer 
