<TEXT>
remember the day of the triffids the sciencefiction 
thriller in which a hail of seeds blossom into fastgrowing plants 
or the musical little shop of horrors in which a talking 
moving plant takes over control 
these it seemed were the stuff movies and fantasies were made 
of 
but a university of miami biophysicist says there actually are 
plants that move 
most plants dont move says thomas j herbert one of a 
handful of scientists interested in how plants move and why they 
bother but a surprising number do although they dont go walking 
around the ground like triffids which are technically 
threeparted leaves 
twelve or 14 plant families have members that can move their 
leaves relatively rapidly says the biophysicist at the coral 
gables fla school the leaves of one sensitive plant he 
says fold up and seem to draw away when touched 
theyre an extreme example because they move so rapidly he 
says 
many legumes members of the pea family are capable of 
conspicuous motion others more commonly react to sunlight and 
water 
herbert says that he hopes by studying plants that are capable of 
movement more can be learned about what conditions are important 
for all plants 
i use them like a little computer says herbert they can 
readjust the position of their leaves for various conditions of sun 
heat water and so forth so observing them is like telling the 
plant find me the leaf angle you like best in these conditions 
and the plant responds and that response we assume is telling us 
whats best for it 
in this way we can begin to understand the needs of other 
plants that cant move 
he says that understanding the needs of plants may lead to the 
adjustment of conditions for plants to the benefit of people 
</TEXT>
