<TEXT>
economic growth will slow significantly this 
year while inflation and interest rates both rise but the country 
should be able to avoid a recession the nations top business 
economists predicted today 
the national association of business economists says a survey of 
its members found them slightly more optimistic about the economys 
fortunes in 1989 than they were just three months ago 
however three out of four of the economists still believe 
president bush will have to deal with an economic downturn in the 
first two years of his presidency 
that represented a decline from the 89 percent who last november 
expected a recession by the end of 1990 and the number predicting a 
recession this year showed an even bigger drop from 40 percent 
three months ago to 19 percent now 
but the belief that the current expansion which has already 
lasted a peacetime record of six years will keep steaming ahead for 
two more years is still a minority view held by just onefourth of 
the economists surveyed 
the median forecast for growth this year as measured by the 
gross national product was 27 percent up slightly from a 25 
percent estimate made three months ago 
that is still onehalf percentage point lower than the bush 
administrations estimate that the gnp will expand at the robust 
clip of 32 percent in 1989 
the administration is counting on faster growth to bring in more 
revenues and help it lower the budget deficit without the need to 
resort to higher taxes 
on the question of interest rates another critical component of 
the budget deficit because of the cost of financing the 27 
trillion national debt the business economists see shortterm rates 
hitting a peak of 85 percent this year and then beginning to 
decline to 78 percent by the end of 1989 
the administration is forecasting substantially lower rates for 
this year 
the survey was taken before the federal reserve boosted the 
discount rate on friday to a threeyear high of 7 percent an 
increase in the discount rate the interest the central bank charges 
to make loans to commercial banks is the most dramatic gesture the 
fed can make to show its determination to push the cost of credit 
higher and dampen inflationary pressures 
the business economists expressed strong support for the feds 
inflationfighting battle with 70 percent expecting the board to 
boost interest rates further in the next six months 
while expressing an urgent need for congress and the 
administration to reach an agreement on a credible deficit reduction 
plan the business economists generally supported bushs stand 
against new taxes only about 15 percent of those surveyed said they 
believed tax increases should be emphasized over cutting government 
spending 
among the government programs which should face the knife a 
large majority of the economists 72 percent favored slashing farm 
subsidies cuts in military spending were favored by 55 percent 
while 47 percent believed social security costofliving increases 
should be pared to reduce the budget deficit 
among those who advocated raising taxes to help get the deficit 
under control the overwhelming favorite place to look was an 
increase in the gasoline tax preferred by 71 percent followed by 
51 percent who said user fees for government services should be 
increased 
on other topics the business economists said 
inflation will worsen this year with consumer prices climbing by 
48 percent compared to an increase of 44 percent in both 1987 and 
1988 
the merchandise trade deficit which dropped by 20 percent to 
137 billion last year will continue improving but at a slower rate 
in 1989 falling by 12 percent to 120 billion 
unemployment will show little change averaging 55 percent for 
the year the same as in 1988 this estimate was based on a belief 
that the economy will be expanding enough to take care of new 
entrants into the labor force but not fast enough to make further 
inroads in the jobless rate 
personal consumption spending which accounts for twothirds of 
overall economic activity will grow by 25 percent this year 
little changed from last year with new housing starts and new auto 
sales remaining close to last years levels 
the survey on economic projections was based on responses from 69 
economists who make up the associations economic forecasting panel 
while the assessments of budgetary and monetary policy came from a 
broader survey of nearly 300 of the associations members 
