<TEXT>
japan has decided to alter its monitoring of 
overseas computer chip prices one of the key provisions of a 
semiconductor agreement between it and the united states an 
official said monday 
under the pact reached in 1985 japan pledged it would monitor 
the prices of japanese memory chips sold in third countries as a 
means of discouraging their resale in the united states at cheap 
prices 
the agreement resulted from a series of complaints by us 
semiconductor makers that japanese companies had sold memory chips 
in the united states below their fair market price a practice known 
as dumping 
the monitoring provision has been sharply criticized by european 
countries which charged it regulated prices in other nations and 
therefore violated the rules of the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade an international trade organization 
in a ruling last march the gatt said the european complaint was 
valid 
the thirdcountry monitoring is not consistent with the gatt 
so we will have to modify the agreement said taizo nakatomi an 
official in the ministry of international trade and industry 
he said a high ministry official tetsu mizuno left for 
washington on sunday to discuss a modification of the pact with us 
trade officials 
the yomiuri shimbun japans largest newspaper reported that 
mizuno will seek us consent to discontinue the thirdcountry 
monitoring but nakatomi said mizuno had no concrete position and 
would try to reach a compromise with the united states on how to 
change the provision 
under the arrangement with the united states we have an 
obligation to monitor prices and sales but the european community 
is saying that we have to completely modify the provision thats a 
dilemma for us nakatomi said 
he said the japanese government hoped to find a middle ground 
between the two extremes 
in the bilateral semiconductor agreement japan also pledged to 
set a fair price for exports of certain key memory chips to the 
united states establish a supply and demand forecast committee 
intended to stabilize prices and supply of memory chips and 
increase the sales of usmade semiconductors in japan 
in april 1987 the united states imposed 300 million in tariffs 
on japan as a penalty for having allegedly violated the agreement by 
continuing to dump memory chips and reneging on the pledge to 
improve market access 
two months later the united states reduced the penalties by 135 
million after ruling that japanese makers had stopped dumping 
leaving 165 million still in effect because of the market share 
issue 
japan claims it has removed market restrictions and us 
companies must try harder if they want to increase their sales in 
japan 
european countries are currently negotiating a separate 
semiconductor pact with japan that would regulate prices of 
japanesemade memory chips in europe but not in other nations news 
reports say 
the agreement also would not include any pledge by japan to 
increase sales of european chips inside japan the economic weekly 
japan economic journal reported 
