<DOCNO> AP890227-0295 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to revive an 
affirmative action program in south bend ind that called for 
hiring more blacks and hispanics as firefighters and police officers 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that struck down 
the plan after it was challenged by a white man denied a job as a 
firefighter 
the justices themselves last jan 23 struck down an affirmative 
action plan in richmond va that set aside 30 percent of all 
public works contracts for minorityowned businesses 
in that decision the court made it more difficult for local and 
state governments to adopt affirmative action plans that feature 
strict racial quotas 
the justices already have under study and are expected to decide 
by july an affirmative action case involving minority promotions in 
the birmingham ala fire department 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals ruled last december that 
the south bend plan amounted to unlawful reverse discrimination 
because it was based solely on a disparity between the percentage of 
minorities in the citys population and minorities in the police and 
fire departments 
such statistical evidence is too generalized to warrant depriving 
qualified whites of jobs the appeals court said 
the ax falls because the statistical comparison upon which the 
city based its plan focused not on the relevant qualified area labor 
pool but on general population statistics the appeals court said 
south bend officials in developing a voluntary affirmative 
action program in 1979 noted that the citys minority population 
was 14 percent while blacks and hispanics held only 53 percent of 
the fire department jobs 
the plan was aimed at raising the minority composition of the 
firefighting force to equal the minority makeup of the city within 
five years 
the city hired four minority applicants to the fire department 
and one white in november 1980 all passed a qualifying test 
timothy janowiak placed second on the list of white applicants 
he accused the city of racial discrimination when he was not hired 
the 7th circuit court ruled previously that janowiak was the 
victim of illegal bias but that ruling was set aside last year by 
the supreme court which then ordered the appeals court to restudy 
the case in light of recent affirmative action rulings by the 
justices 
the 7th circuit court reaffirmed its previous ruling after the 
new review 
the appeals court noted that the high court last year upheld the 
promotion of a woman to a county transportation job in california 
over a marginally betterqualified man 
but the appeals court said that case is distinct in key respects 
from the south bend plan for giving preferential treatment to 
minorities 
the appeals court said that in the california case there was a 
manifest imbalance between the number of women employed by the 
county in skilled craft positions and the number of women in the 
local labor pool of skilled craft workers 
what constitutes a manifest imbalance remains unclear 
the appeals court said 
but it said that in any event south bend officials did not focus 
on the relevant qualified area labor pool but rather on the 
general city minority population in adopting an affirmative action 
plan 
south bends voluntary affirmative action plan therefore 
fails to pass legal muster the appeals court said 
the case is south bend vs janowiak 871754 
</TEXT>
