<TEXT>
housing construction starts declined 1 percent in 
the fourth quarter compared with the same period of 1987 and the 
apartment market remained especially weak according to a private 
report monday 
for all of 1988 construction was begun on 9 percent fewer 
dwelling units than in 1987 fw dodge group of mcgrawhill 
information services co said housing starts declined 14 percent in 
1987 from 1986 
the stability of singlefamily home building over the past few 
years stands in sharp contrast to the virtual collapse of apartment 
construction george a christie chief economist of fw dodge 
said in a written statement 
singlefamily home construction fell 7 percent over the two years 
from 1986 to 1988 to 101 million units while multifamily 
dwelling construction plummeted 41 percent to 448000 units over the 
same period christie said 
housing starts reached their peak of the decade at 185 million 
units in 1986 before falling to 159 million in 1987 and 146 
million in 1988 
apartment construction was stimulated beyond demand by tax 
incentives in the mid1980s and vacancies remain high christie said 
construction of onefamily houses has remained stable at 1 
million to 11 million a year for the past three years he said 
this year higher interest rates should hurt the singlefamily 
housing market more than the apartment market he said 
the california housing market was stimulated in 1988 by 
developers rushing to beat nogrowth initiatives on the state 
ballot christie said the initiatives were defeated 
leading the nation in housing starts in the fourth quarter was 
the los angeleslong beach are at 10473 units up 2 percent over 
the 1987 fourth quarter 
rounding out the top 10 were riversidesan bernardino calif 
9449 up 15 percent atlanta 9316 units down 3 percent 
washington 9306 down 27 percent philadelphia 6072 down 1 
percent chicago 6058 up 7 percent las vegas 5469 up 115 
percent seattle 5467 down 19 percent west palm beachboca 
ratondelray beach fla 5442 up 19 percent and detroit 5134 
down 2 percent 
