<TEXT>
foreign companies are ready to resume largescale 
steel dumping on the united states if voluntary restraints on the 
amount of imported steel are not continued this fall the president 
of the uss division of usx corp said monday 
thomas graham said a 5year renewal of the limits wich expire 
sept 30 is essential for the us steel industry to continue its 
2year financial comeback 
we cant afford to become giddy he said two years of 
profitability doesnt offset five years of losses 
graham said the us steel industry earned more than 2 billion 
in 1988 and about 900 million the year before but between 1982 and 
1986 the industry lost 12 billion an average of 24 billion 
annually 
the voluntary restraint agreement which began in 1984 limits 
the amount of imported finished steel to 185 percent of the us 
market among other things the american institute for imported 
steel said steel made overseas and shipped to the united states 
accounts for about 177 percent of the market below the current vra 
limit 
despite that graham said the us government must hold the line 
on the amount of steel coming into the country 
theres no doubt that foreign producers will revert to 
largescale dumping of heavily subsidized steel without a vra 
renewal he said we certainly cant tolerate a return to past 
practices 
in the third quarter of 1984 shortly before the vra began 
imported steel made up just more than 30 percent of the us market 
grahams comments came during the opening day of the weeklong 
annual congress of the society of automotive engineers 
the imported steel association which supports an elimination of 
the vra or a 2year extension instead of five years has claimed 
that the limits reduce supply thereby increasing prices for us 
steel something the domestic steelmakers like 
but graham dismissed that contention 
its not an issue of protectionism he said its an issue 
of legal trading practices 
graham also said pittsburghbased uss is prepared to file legal 
papers if the bush administration rejects a vra extension 
we need enabling legislation from congress before the bush 
administration has the ability to act he said we see ourselves 
as prudent businessmen 
he declined to say when any legal moves may be taken adding that 
an earlier agreement barred the industry from filing trade 
litigation while a vra was in effect 
