a stockbroker testified in the gaf corp 
securities fraud trial monday that he tried to fix the price of a 
company stock but contradicted a key government informant who said 
the broker took some orders directly from gaf 
james melton head trader for jefferies amp co took the stand in 
the first wall street fraud case to be heard by a jury one month 
after suffering a heart attack in los angeles that delayed his 
testimony 
melton 45 backed up the account of trader boyd l jefferies 
who said in us district court earlier this month that gaf asked 
him to inflate the stock price of union carbide corp to 22 a share 
in october 1986 
but under crossexamination melton contradicted jefferies 
testimony that melton pursued carbide stock in early november 1986 
under orders from gaf vice chairman james t sherwin who was 
indicted along with the company last july 
i dont recall mr sherwin ever telling me to do anything with 
union carbide melton said 
jefferies had testified that his firm bought 190000 union 
carbide shares at sherwins request in two days in october as part 
of the scheme 
the purpose of the alleged stock manipulation was to maximize 
gafs gain from the sale of its holding in union carbide after a 
failed takeover attempt of the much larger chemical company wayne 
njbased gaf sold about 5 million carbide shares in november 1986 
for 23 each 
melton said jefferies ordered him to buy union carbide stock 
through the new york stock exchange and keep it at a certain price 
and to report directly to sherwin each day he traded the stock 
he said some days he also bought stock through exchanges in los 
angeles and san francisco to support prices in new york 
my mission was to close the stock at 22 dollars or higher 
melton testified under questioning from assistant us attorney carl 
loewenson jr he said he sometimes bought everything for sale 
i told mr sherwin what i had done and the price at which it 
had closed melton said he said thank you 
the trial is in its second incarnation us district judge mary 
johnson lowe ordered a mistrial on jan 10 four weeks into the case 
after concluding prosecutors withheld a key piece of evidence from 
the defense 
jefferies struck a plea bargain with government prosecutors in 
1987 after he was implicated in the wall street insider trading 
scandals with jailed speculator ivan boesky 
jefferies agreed to plea guilty to two securities law violations 
quit his brokerage firm and stay out of the securities business for 
at least five years he hasnt been sentenced 
